				\begin{document}$$ V={V}_{\mathrm{max}}\frac{I^n}{k^n+{I}^n}, $$\end{document}V=VmaxInkn+In,in which Vmax is the maximal response amplitude, k is the intensity required to evoke 50% of Vmax, n is the slope, and I is the stimulus intensity. This relation is called Hill function and is a variation of the Michaelis-Menten equation originally developed for enzyme kinetics [29]. Since the area-intensity relationship of OPs has a biphasic nature, two light intensities were compared: (i) an intermediate intensity (intensity #8, 1.56 log photons*μm−2*s−1), corresponding to a first plateau in this relationship and well within the scotopic (rod-driven) range for the mouse [30] and (ii) the last intensity (intensity #13, 4.09 log photons*μm−2*s−1), which is in the mesopic/photopic range and reflects therefore cone-driven activity [30].
